11 Further amend said bill, Page 32, Section 339.100, Line 165, by inserting after said section and
12 line the following:
13
14 "506.400. 1. As used in this section, "claimant" means a person convicted and
15 subsequently imprisoned for one or more offenses that such person did not commit.
16 2. Notwithstanding any other provision of law, a claimant may bring an action in the
17 circuit court seeking damages from the state under this section.
18 3. (1) The claimant shall establish the following by a preponderance of evidence:
19 (a) The claimant was convicted of a felony offense and subsequently imprisoned;
20 (b) The claimant's judgment of conviction was reversed or vacated and either the charges
21 were dismissed or on retrial the claimant was found to be not guilty;
22 (c) The claimant did not commit the offense or offenses for which the claimant was
23 convicted and was not an accessory or accomplice to the acts that were the basis of the
24 conviction and resulted in a reversal or vacation of the judgment of conviction, dismissal of the
25 charges, or finding of not guilty on retrial; and
26 (d) The claimant did not commit or suborn perjury, fabricate evidence, or by the
27 claimant's own conduct cause or bring about the conviction. Neither a confession or admission
28 later found to be false nor a guilty plea shall constitute committing or suborning perjury,
29 fabricating evidence, or causing or bringing about the conviction under this subsection.
30 (2) The court, in exercising its discretion as permitted by law regarding the weight and
31 admissibility of evidence submitted under this section, may, in the interest of justice, give due
32 consideration to difficulties of proof caused by the passage of time, the death or unavailability of
33 witnesses, the destruction of evidence, or other factors not caused by such persons or those
34 acting on their behalf.
35 4. (1) The suit, accompanied by a statement of the facts concerning the claim for
36 damages, verified in the manner provided for the verification of complaints in the rules of civil
37 procedure, shall be brought by the claimant within a period of two years after the:
Page 7 of 12

5011H04.01H
1 (a) Dismissal of the criminal charges against the claimant or finding of not guilty on
2 retrial; or
3 (b) Grant of a pardon to the claimant.
4 (2) A claimant convicted, imprisoned, and released from custody before August 28,
5 2026, shall commence an action under this section no later than August 28, 2028.
6 (3) All pleadings shall be captioned "In the matter of the wrongful conviction of".
7 (4) Any claim filed under this section shall be served on the attorney general.
8 (5) The suit for a claim filed under this section shall be tried by the court, and no request
9 for a jury trial shall be made.
10 5. (1) Damages awarded under this section shall be:
11 (a) Except as provided in subdivision (2) of this subsection, one hundred seventy-nine
12 dollars per day for each day of imprisonment but no more than sixty-five thousand dollars per
13 fiscal year; and
14 (b) Not less than twenty-five thousand dollars for each additional year served on parole
15 or postrelease supervision or each additional year the claimant was required to register as a
16 sexual offender under sections 589.400 to 589.425, whichever is greater.
17 (2) A claimant shall not receive compensation for any period of incarceration during
18 which the claimant was concurrently serving a sentence for a conviction of another crime for
19 which such claimant was lawfully incarcerated.
20 (3) (a) Except as provided in paragraph (b) of this subdivision, the court shall order that
21 the award be paid as a combination of an initial payment not to exceed one hundred thousand
22 dollars or twenty-five percent of the award, whichever is greater, and the remainder as an annuity
23 not to exceed eighty thousand dollars per year. The claimant shall designate a beneficiary or
24 beneficiaries for the annuity by filing such designation with the court.
25 (b) The court may order that the award be paid in one lump sum if the court finds that it
26 is in the best interests of the claimant.
27 (4) In addition to the damages awarded under subdivision (1) of this subsection, the
28 claimant:
29 (a) Shall be entitled to receive reasonable attorney's fees and costs incurred in the action
30 brought under this section not to exceed a total of twenty-five thousand dollars, unless a greater
31 reasonable total is authorized by the court upon a finding of good cause shown;
32 (b) May also be awarded other nonmonetary relief as sought in the complaint including,
33 but not limited to, counseling, housing assistance, and personal financial literacy assistance, as
34 appropriate; and
35 (c) Shall be entitled to receive tuition assistance under section 506.403.
36 6. (1) If, at the time of the judgment entry referred to in subsection 5 of this section, the
37 claimant has won a monetary award against the state or any political subdivision thereof in a
38 civil action related to the same subject, or has entered into a settlement agreement with the state
Page 8 of 12

5011H04.01H
1 or any political subdivision thereof related to the same subject, the amount of the award in the
2 action or the amount received in the settlement agreement, less any sums paid to attorneys or for
3 costs in litigating the other civil action or obtaining the settlement agreement, shall be deducted
4 from the sum of moneys to which the claimant is entitled under this section. The court shall
5 include in the judgment entry an award to the state of any amount deducted under this
6 subsection.
7 (2) If subdivision (1) of this subsection does not apply and if, after the time of the
8 judgment entry referred to in subsection 5 of this section, the claimant wins a monetary award
9 against the state or any political subdivision thereof in a civil action related to the same subject,
10 or enters into a settlement agreement with the state or any political subdivision thereof related to
11 the same subject, the claimant shall reimburse the state for the sum of moneys paid under the
12 judgment entry referred to in subsection 5 of this section, less any sums paid to attorneys or for
13 costs in litigating the other civil action or obtaining the settlement agreement. A reimbursement
14 required under this subsection shall not exceed the amount of the monetary award the claimant
15 wins for damages in the other civil action or the amount received in the settlement agreement.
16 7. If the court finds that the claimant is entitled to a judgment, it shall enter a certificate
17 of innocence finding that the claimant was innocent of all offenses for which the claimant was
18 mistakenly convicted. The clerk of the court shall send a certified copy of the certificate of
19 innocence and the judgment entry to the attorney general for payment under section 105.711.
20 8. Upon entry of a certificate of innocence, the claimant shall automatically be granted
21 an order of expungement from the court in which he or she pled guilty or was sentenced to
22 expunge from all official records or recordations of his or her arrest, plea, trial, or conviction.
23 Upon granting of the order of expungement, the records and files maintained in any
24 administrative or court proceeding in an associate or circuit division of the court shall be
25 confidential and only available to the parties or by order of the court for good cause shown. The
26 effect of such order shall be to restore such person to the status he or she occupied prior to such
27 arrest, plea, or conviction and as if such event had never taken place. No person as to whom
28 such order has been entered shall be held thereafter under any provision of any law to be guilty
29 of perjury or otherwise giving a false statement by reason of his or her failure to recite or
30 acknowledge such arrest, plea, trial, conviction, or expungement in response to any inquiry made
31 of him or her for any purpose whatsoever, and no such inquiry shall be made for information
32 relating to an expungement under this subsection.
33 9. Upon entry of a certificate of innocence, the court shall order the expungement and
34 destruction of the associated biological samples authorized by and given to the Missouri state
35 highway patrol. The order shall state the information required to be stated in a petition to
36 expunge and destroy the samples and profile record and shall direct the Missouri state highway
37 patrol to expunge and destroy such samples and profile record. The clerk of the court shall send
38 a certified copy of the order to the Missouri state highway patrol, which shall carry out the order
Page 9 of 12

5011H04.01H
1 and provide confirmation of such action to the court. Nothing in this subsection shall require the
2 Missouri state highway patrol to expunge and destroy any sample or profile record associated
3 with the claimant that was related to any offense other than the offense for which the court has
4 entered a certificate of innocence.
5 10. The decision to grant or deny a certificate of innocence shall not have a res judicata
6 effect on any other proceedings.
7 11. Nothing in this section shall preclude the department of corrections from providing a
8 claimant reentry services that are provided to other persons including, but not limited to,
9 financial assistance, housing assistance, mentoring, and counseling. Such services shall be
10 provided while an action under this section is pending and after any judgment is entered, as
11 appropriate for such claimant.
12 12. A decision under this section may be appealed to the supreme court.
13 506.403. 1. Any individual awarded tuition assistance under section 506.400 shall
14 receive a waiver of tuition and required fees for attendance at a public institution of higher
15 education for up to one hundred twenty credit hours. Such individual may attend a public
16 institution of higher education either full-time or part-time.
17 2. (1) Subject to appropriations, the department of higher education may make
